464
00:28:44,681 --> 00:28:46,599
<i>And I said, "Well, Your Honor,</i>

465
00:28:46,683 --> 00:28:50,061
<i>we did not try to say exactly</i>
<i>what moment that was."</i>

466
00:28:50,145 --> 00:28:53,231
<i>There is no one answer to that.</i>

467
00:28:53,356 --> 00:28:57,360
<i>Different religions</i>
<i>have different answers to that question,</i>

468
00:28:57,444 --> 00:29:00,405
<i>but there is no legal standard that said,</i>

469
00:29:00,488 --> 00:29:03,616
<i>"At this point the fetus becomes a human."</i>

470
00:29:03,700 --> 00:29:07,287
So, the question is,
who gets to make the decision?

471
00:29:07,620 --> 00:29:09,414
Is it the woman,

472
00:29:09,497 --> 00:29:11,416
or is it the government?

473
00:29:11,499 --> 00:29:15,253
And my position has always been
it's not the government.

474
00:29:15,879 --> 00:29:17,756
Good evening. In a landmark ruling,

475
00:29:17,839 --> 00:29:21,092
the Supreme Court today
legalized abortion.

476
00:29:21,176 --> 00:29:22,677
[reporter] <i>The Court split seven to two</i>

477
00:29:22,761 --> 00:29:25,513
<i>with Justices Byron White</i>
<i>and William Rehnquist dissenting.</i>

478
00:29:25,764 --> 00:29:28,808
<i>The decision made abortion</i>
<i>largely a private matter</i>

479
00:29:28,892 --> 00:29:31,603
<i>and ordered the states</i>
<i>to make no laws forbidding it,</i> <i>except possibly during the final months.</i>

480
00:29:34,481 --> 00:29:37,901
When Roe went through,
it was a shock to everyone.

481
00:29:37,984 --> 00:29:40,987
To go so far over to the other side,

482
00:29:41,070 --> 00:29:44,282
to put everything in the woman's hand
and essentially dismantle the laws.

483
00:29:44,365 --> 00:29:47,327
Now, in any other state,
you couldn't pass laws against abortion,

484
00:29:47,410 --> 00:29:49,287
not forbidding it directly.

485
00:29:49,370 --> 00:29:50,663
It was a constitutional right.

486
00:29:52,207 --> 00:29:53,875
[Greenhouse] <i>The Roe decision held</i>

487
00:29:53,958 --> 00:29:56,753
<i>that women have the right</i>
<i>to terminate a pregnancy</i>

488
00:29:56,878 --> 00:29:58,671
<i>in the first two trimesters,</i>

489
00:29:59,214 --> 00:30:01,716
<i>and then it's only at the third trimester</i>

490
00:30:01,800 --> 00:30:04,636
<i>that the state has the right</i>
<i>to prohibit abortion</i>

491
00:30:04,719 --> 00:30:09,224
<i>except when necessary to preserve</i>
<i>a woman's life or health.</i>

492
00:30:11,226 --> 00:30:13,561
[Wattleton] <i>When the Roe v. Wade decision</i>
<i>was handed down,</i>

493
00:30:14,395 --> 00:30:17,607
<i>Planned Parenthood had been devoted</i>
<i>to women's reproductive health</i>

494
00:30:17,690 --> 00:30:21,319
<i>and access to contraception.</i>

495
00:30:21,402 --> 00:30:24,197
<i>And the local chapters</i>
<i>had to ask themselves,</i>

496
00:30:24,572 --> 00:30:27,992
<i>"Are we gonna provide abortions</i>
<i>now that they are legal?"</i>

497
00:30:28,618 --> 00:30:31,454
It was really a moment of reflection

498
00:30:31,538 --> 00:30:33,832
that was very tough
for the organization.

499
00:30:33,915 --> 00:30:35,667
[woman] March 11th is...

500
00:30:35,750 --> 00:30:37,293
[Rev. Davis] <i>When it first became legal,</i>

501
00:30:37,377 --> 00:30:40,213
<i>Planned Parenthood was not keen</i>
