00:47:47,322 --> 00:47:49,449
So, you're not a physician.
Are you a pathologist?

801
00:47:49,533 --> 00:47:50,367
Not at all.

802
00:47:51,493 --> 00:47:52,661
Which is infuriating.

803
00:47:53,161 --> 00:47:57,499
Especially from sort of the standpoint
of science and evidence and...

804
00:47:58,250 --> 00:47:59,418
just facts.

805
00:47:59,710 --> 00:48:03,380
The abortion clinic in St. Louis
has not been complying with the law

806
00:48:03,463 --> 00:48:05,424
in terms of turning over
complication reports.

807
00:48:06,341 --> 00:48:09,511
Every year we have
dozens of pro-life bills introduced.

808
00:48:10,470 --> 00:48:14,016
Lawmakers who come to me and say,
"Sam, what can I do?"

809
00:48:14,182 --> 00:48:17,895
What type of bill can I introduce
to reduce abortions?"

810
00:48:18,979 --> 00:48:23,358
<i>It's a bit of a cat and mouse game</i>
<i>between the pro-life pro-choice side,</i>

811
00:48:23,817 --> 00:48:25,819
...is not turning in complication reports. [reporter] <i>Once again a bill on</i>
<i>abortion regulations</i>

812
00:48:28,447 --> 00:48:29,781
<i>moved through the legislature.</i>

813
00:48:29,865 --> 00:48:31,658
They have to have a complication plan.

814
00:48:31,992 --> 00:48:33,452
This is how I feel.

815
00:48:34,328 --> 00:48:37,372
Okay? We're not
in the field of medicine here.

816
00:48:37,539 --> 00:48:41,084
When did the government start approving
complication plans?

817
00:48:41,376 --> 00:48:43,420
I thought the doctors
or the physicians would do that.

818
00:48:43,503 --> 00:48:46,131
Our complaint is that
that should be for all clinics.

819
00:48:46,214 --> 00:48:49,468
if abortion facilities have to comply
with certain things, then

820
00:48:49,551 --> 00:48:53,972
so too should other clinics that are
providing similar levels of care.

821
00:48:54,514 --> 00:48:56,516
Are you putting plans together
for anything else?

822
00:48:56,600 --> 00:48:58,310
I mean, you could eat too much pork!

823
00:48:58,393 --> 00:49:00,854
And have a gallstone
and you'd have to go through surgery.

824
00:49:00,938 --> 00:49:02,606
Why is it that we're just doing this

825
00:49:02,689 --> 00:49:05,651
when it comes to individuals
wanting to have an abortion?

826
00:49:06,360 --> 00:49:08,987
-Well, I mean it is--
-It sounds so ridiculous.

827
00:49:09,529 --> 00:49:12,783
[Lee] <i>Abortion is different</i>
<i>than just any other medical procedure.</i>

828
00:49:13,241 --> 00:49:15,869
<i>I know that the Democrats</i>
<i>and Planned Parenthood</i>

829
00:49:15,953 --> 00:49:18,830
want to treat it that way. I know
they want to talk about in that way.

830
00:49:18,914 --> 00:49:20,999
But talk to your average person
on the street.

831
00:49:21,083 --> 00:49:24,169
And they're going to tell you
that abortion is not the same as having

832
00:49:24,336 --> 00:49:26,129
a colonoscopy or having your tooth pulled.

833
00:49:26,380 --> 00:49:28,590
It's something unique and different.

834
00:49:28,674 --> 00:49:30,759
There is no other medical procedure, none,

835
00:49:30,842 --> 00:49:34,346
not one, that is legislated
in the way that abortion is.

836
00:49:35,055 --> 00:49:36,390
Enough is enough.

837
00:49:36,640 --> 00:49:40,894
I'm ready to go down fighting,
because I'm tired of the Republican Party

838
00:49:41,186 --> 00:49:45,607
bullying women when it comes
to their right to choose.

839
00:49:46,650 --> 00:49:48,026
[man] I'll tell you what.

840
00:49:48,110 --> 00:49:52,656
I am proud to be with so many people
standing for life here in Missouri.

841
00:49:53,782 --> 00:49:58,120
[crowd chanting indistinctly]

842
00:49:58,912 --> 00:50:00,205
Message received. Thank you--

843
00:50:00,372 --> 00:50:02,416
[Greenhouse] <i>You know,</i>
<i>from the perspective of today,</i>

844
00:50:02,499 --> 00:50:06,670
<i>I think it's important to remember that</i>
<i>abortion was not always so partisan</i> <i>and it wasn't always a requirement</i>
<i>for the Republicans to be pro-life.</i>

845
00:50:14,928 --> 00:50:18,432
<i>In fact, it took years of cultivation...</i>

846
00:50:18,515 --> 00:50:20,934
[man] <i>We're concerned that</i>
<i>a million babies are dying...</i>

847
00:50:21,018 --> 00:50:24,855
[Greenhouse]
<i>...by very smart Republican strategists.</i>

848
00:50:24,938 --> 00:50:29,276
<i>It took years to bring about</i>
<i>that kind of party realignment,</i>

849
00:50:29,359 --> 00:50:32,863
<i>the placing of abortion</i>
<i>front-and-center as</i>

850
00:50:33,071 --> 00:50:35,824
<i>a social, cultural issue in our politics.</i>

851
00:50:35,907 --> 00:50:39,619
We're concerned about the moral problems,
the breakdown of the family.

852
00:50:39,953 --> 00:50:43,957
We've come to seek
the welfare of America's children.

853
00:50:44,041 --> 00:50:45,709
God bless you and have a great day.

854
00:50:47,127 --> 00:50:51,298
[Greenhouse] <i>And it was accomplished in</i>
<i>the 1980s, by this coalition</i>

855
00:50:51,882 --> 00:50:55,969
<i>of social and religious</i>
<i>and political conservatives.</i>

856
00:50:57,220 --> 00:50:59,681
<i>And it was done</i>
<i>with the rise of Ronald Reagan.</i>

857
00:51:02,726 --> 00:51:05,854
[man] <i>The 1980 election is when abortion</i>

858
00:51:05,937 --> 00:51:10,484
<i>really becomes a political issue</i>
<i>and particularly a Republican issue.</i>

859
00:51:11,068 --> 00:51:13,487
[Falwell] <i>We have</i>
<i>a threefold primary responsibility.</i>

860
00:51:13,570 --> 00:51:16,448
<i>Number one, get people saved.</i>
<i>Number two, get them baptized.</i>

861
00:51:16,531 --> 00:51:18,158
<i>Number three,</i>
<i>get them registered to vote.</i>

862
00:51:20,243 --> 00:51:25,082
[man]<i> Falwell saw evangelical Christians</i>
<i>as the basis for a political movement.</i>

863
00:51:25,999 --> 00:51:29,586
Falwell wanted to organize evangelical
voters, who up until that time

864
00:51:29,878 --> 00:51:31,588
had not been politically active.

865
00:51:31,838 --> 00:51:35,425
[Reagan] It's always seemed to me
we haven't improved by one iota

866
00:51:35,926 --> 00:51:37,219
on the Ten Commandments.

867
00:51:40,222 --> 00:51:43,517
[Balmer] <i>Falwell and the religious right</i>
<i>identifies</i>

868
00:51:43,683 --> 00:51:47,854
<i>Ronald Reagan as a candidate</i>
<i>who would push their agenda,</i>

869
00:51:47,938 --> 00:51:49,564
<i>their socially conservative agenda.</i>

870
00:51:50,398 --> 00:51:52,442
Religious America is awakening,

871
00:51:52,901 --> 00:51:55,987
perhaps just in time,
for our country's sake.

872
00:51:57,906 --> 00:52:00,951
[Balmer] <i>But what got evangelical leaders</i>
<i>interested in politics</i>

873
00:52:01,034 --> 00:52:03,286
<i>was this notion that the Bible</i>

874
00:52:03,495 --> 00:52:06,498
<i>mandated the separation of the races.</i>

875
00:52:07,249 --> 00:52:11,294
<i>And several so-called segregation</i>
<i>academies were applying</i>

876
00:52:11,378 --> 00:52:13,380
<i>for tax-exempt status.</i>

877
00:52:13,964 --> 00:52:18,301
<i>And the district court ruled</i>
<i>that any organization that engages</i>

878
00:52:18,385 --> 00:52:21,221
<i>in racial segregation, or discrimination,</i>

879
00:52:21,346 --> 00:52:23,515
cannot claim tax-exempt status.

880
00:52:24,724 --> 00:52:26,810
That was the catalyst

881
00:52:26,893 --> 00:52:29,688
<i>for the religious right</i>
<i>becoming politically active.</i>

882
00:52:29,771 --> 00:52:31,064
We have a fight going on...

883
00:52:31,481 --> 00:52:35,318
on the question of tax exemptions
for Christian schools.

884
00:52:35,902 --> 00:52:39,322
[Melich] <i>Paul Weyrich</i>
<i>was one of the chief strategists of</i>

885
00:52:39,406 --> 00:52:40,740
<i>the New Right movement.</i>

886
00:52:40,824 --> 00:52:43,285
Questions involved
are religious liberty questions.

887
00:52:43,368 --> 00:52:48,415
It was a movement that said
we are going to win the presidency

888
00:52:48,832 --> 00:52:52,752
through bigotry, but we are not going
to come right out and say it.

889
00:52:52,878 --> 00:52:55,046
This coming election's gonna be
a big test for us...

890
00:52:55,672 --> 00:52:59,050
This election is to make America
great again.

891
00:52:59,759 --> 00:53:01,803
[Weyrich] <i>I have told the Republicans</i>

892
00:53:01,887 --> 00:53:05,307
<i>that you are loyal to a certain set</i>
<i>of moral precepts</i>

893
00:53:05,432 --> 00:53:06,892
in which you deeply believe.

894
00:53:07,726 --> 00:53:10,812
[Balmer] <i>Weyrich recognized</i>
<i>the electoral potential</i>

895
00:53:11,188 --> 00:53:15,358
of evangelical voters,
but he needed a populist issue

896
00:53:15,775 --> 00:53:19,404
that would appeal more generally
to religious voters.

897
00:53:19,905 --> 00:53:21,698
<i>And he was savvy enough to recognize</i>

898
00:53:21,865 --> 00:53:25,243
<i>that overt racism probably wouldn't work</i>
<i>on a wide scale.</i>

899
00:53:30,248 --> 00:53:33,418
[woman] <i>The pro-family movement</i>
<i>and the American people do not want</i>

900
00:53:33,501 --> 00:53:38,340
the women's lib ideology forced
upon all the rest of us.

901
00:53:39,007 --> 00:53:41,927
[Balmer] <i>Phyllis Schlafly had been able</i>
<i>to mobilize</i>

902
00:53:42,010 --> 00:53:44,554
voters around moral issues.

903
00:53:44,638 --> 00:53:47,057
Well, I am certainly opposed to abortion,

904
00:53:47,140 --> 00:53:49,267
because I think it's killing
an unborn child.

905
00:53:51,061 --> 00:53:53,855
[Balmer] <i>And as the presidential election</i>
<i>begins to take shape...</i>

906
00:53:53,939 --> 00:53:56,066
[Weyrich] <i>What are the key issues?</i>
<i>In our judgment,</i>

907
00:53:56,149 --> 00:53:57,317
the right to life,

908
00:53:57,859 --> 00:54:00,779
<i>protect the unborn. These are key issues.</i>

909
00:54:01,571 --> 00:54:03,323
[Balmer] <i>Weyrich says, in effect,</i>

910
00:54:03,531 --> 00:54:04,991
"We found our issue.

911
00:54:05,367 --> 00:54:09,162
Abortion is going to work for us
as a political issue."

912
00:54:09,496 --> 00:54:13,166
Millions of unborn defenseless babies...

913
00:54:13,333 --> 00:54:15,085
[Melich] <i>When you are trying to</i>

914
00:54:15,502 --> 00:54:20,006
<i>change the dynamic</i>
<i>of the political system in the country,</i>

915
00:54:21,132 --> 00:54:24,177
<i>you have to do it</i>
<i>through emotional issues.</i>

916
00:54:25,095 --> 00:54:27,722
In our Washington studios
is Jerry Falwell.

917
00:54:27,806 --> 00:54:31,810
America has violated the principle
of the dignity of life since 1973.

918
00:54:31,977 --> 00:54:34,646
And we're very strongly pro-life.
Our first order of business--

919
00:54:34,729 --> 00:54:38,400
And what is more emotional
than motherhood and babies?

920
00:54:40,318 --> 00:54:44,781
At that point the Reagan campaign begins
to embrace abortion as a political issue.

921
00:54:44,864 --> 00:54:45,865
I believe that...

922
00:54:46,366 --> 00:54:50,036
that when you interrupt the pregnancy,
you are taking a human life.

923
00:54:50,620 --> 00:54:53,498
[Balmer] <i>Which they ride through</i>
<i>the 1980 election.</i>

924
00:54:54,708 --> 00:54:57,544
[Robertson]<i> It's interesting.</i>
<i>One of the nation's leading pollsters</i>

925
00:54:57,627 --> 00:55:00,255
<i>says Reagan is winning the votes</i>
<i>of the white electors,</i>

926
00:55:00,338 --> 00:55:03,425
<i>who are followers</i>
<i>of the evangelical preachers,</i>

927
00:55:03,508 --> 00:55:06,511
<i>the so-called Moral Majority,</i>
<i>who have been active in the election.</i>

928
00:55:06,720 --> 00:55:10,807
This group is providing Reagan
with his clear margin

929
00:55:11,099 --> 00:55:13,101
in the election. [reporter]
<i>Ronald Reagan's overwhelming victory...</i>

930
00:55:19,065 --> 00:55:22,777
<i>Reagan won 44 states,</i>
<i>with 479 electoral votes.</i>

931
00:55:24,612 --> 00:55:28,700
[Melich] <i>They set out to change</i>
<i>the dynamic in the Republican party.</i>

932
00:55:28,950 --> 00:55:33,663
So they nominated somebody
that would be useful. And they succeeded.

933
00:55:38,126 --> 00:55:40,879
[Lee] It was<i> now eight years</i>
<i>after Roe versus Wade.</i>

934
00:55:42,130 --> 00:55:44,841
<i>And it seemed</i>
<i>like the future of ending abortion</i>

935
00:55:45,008 --> 00:55:46,801
<i>was going to be in the Republican party.</i>

936
00:55:46,885 --> 00:55:49,387
And Reagan really gave a lot of hope
to the pro-life community.

937
00:55:50,430 --> 00:55:53,892
[reporter] Can a person be a Christian
and support federal funding of abortion?

938
00:55:54,476 --> 00:55:57,354
I believe in an abortion
you are taking a human life.

939
00:55:58,146 --> 00:56:01,649
If you believe that, it very definitely
has a religious connotation.

940
00:56:02,817 --> 00:56:05,362
He just reaffirmed his support of

941
00:56:05,445 --> 00:56:08,073
everything the pro-life
movement represents.

942
00:56:08,615 --> 00:56:11,159
There's never been any question
that he was with us.

943
00:56:11,242 --> 00:56:13,328
[protesters] We love life! We want life!

944
00:56:13,411 --> 00:56:15,914
[Lee] <i>In the mind of the pro-life</i>
<i>community, the right to abortion</i>

945
00:56:16,081 --> 00:56:17,874
<i>was an aberration in the law.</i>

946
00:56:18,416 --> 00:56:20,293
So, with the election of President Reagan,

947
00:56:21,252 --> 00:56:24,589
we thought the next step would be
to try to reverse Roe versus Wade.

948
00:56:25,048 --> 00:56:28,051
[chanting] We want life!

949
00:56:32,847 --> 00:56:35,892
[Schlafly] <i>It is the Supreme Court</i>
<i>that has abolished prayer</i>

950
00:56:35,975 --> 00:56:38,561
<i>and the Ten Commandments</i>
<i>from the public schools.</i>

951
00:56:41,272 --> 00:56:43,400
<i>It is Supreme Court decisions</i>

952
00:56:43,483 --> 00:56:47,862
<i>that have brought upon us forced busing</i>
<i>and put our children on buses</i>

953
00:56:47,946 --> 00:56:50,782
<i>and send them across town to some school</i>

954
00:56:50,865 --> 00:56:53,118
<i>that their parents don't want them</i>
<i>to go to.</i>

955
00:56:53,701 --> 00:56:55,412
<i>It is Supreme Court decisions</i>

956
00:56:55,912 --> 00:56:57,914
<i>that have unleashed the pornography</i>

957
00:56:57,997 --> 00:57:01,167
<i>that has invaded our newsstands</i>
<i>and our television.</i>

958
00:57:01,584 --> 00:57:03,420
<i>It is Supreme Court decisions</i>

959
00:57:03,503 --> 00:57:07,799
<i>that have abolished capital punishment</i>
<i>and deterrents against crime.</i>

960
00:57:08,842 --> 00:57:12,011
And, of course,
it is the Supreme Court decision

961
00:57:12,345 --> 00:57:15,932
that has brought about
this tragic evil of our time.

962
00:57:16,015 --> 00:57:19,519
A Supreme Court decision, in 1973,

963
00:57:19,686 --> 00:57:24,816
that invented this new right of a woman
to kill her unborn baby.

964
00:57:27,026 --> 00:57:29,154
[Lee] <i>If abortion is</i>
<i>a constitutional right,</i>

965
00:57:29,404 --> 00:57:32,282
<i>the most important thing was</i>
<i>to overturn Roe versus Wade.</i>

966
00:57:32,490 --> 00:57:35,660
In order to do that, you had to change
the justices on the Court.

967
00:57:35,785 --> 00:57:36,870
There's no other way.

968
00:57:37,745 --> 00:57:42,125
You need, as quickly as possible,
a reconstituting of the Supreme Court.

969
00:57:42,750 --> 00:57:45,795
<i>We just didn't think that the current</i>
<i>justices would have changed their minds.</i>

970
00:57:46,129 --> 00:57:47,589
[Reagan] <i>I will send to the Senate</i>

971
00:57:47,672 --> 00:57:51,009
the nomination
of Judge Sandra Day O'Connor, of Arizona.

972
00:57:51,634 --> 00:57:53,761
<i>[reporter] The first woman on</i>
<i>the Supreme Court,</i>

973
00:57:53,845 --> 00:57:55,096
<i>Judge Sandra Day O'Connor.</i>

974
00:57:56,014 --> 00:57:59,767
She told the Senate today
that she is firmly opposed to abortion.

975
00:57:59,851 --> 00:58:03,146
In the area of abortion is
that I am opposed to it

976
00:58:03,229 --> 00:58:06,232
as a matter of birth control.

977
00:58:06,774 --> 00:58:08,776
[Lee] <i>So, President Reagan</i>
<i>appointed O'Connor,</i>

978
00:58:08,860 --> 00:58:12,322
<i>then appointed Justice Scalia</i>
<i>and Justice Kennedy.</i>

979
00:58:12,447 --> 00:58:16,284
<i>And in the pro-life community there was</i>
<i>the hope that Roe versus Wade</i>

980
00:58:16,743 --> 00:58:17,827
<i>may get overturned.</i>

981
00:58:17,911 --> 00:58:21,331
<i>And we thought the Court was moving</i>
<i>much closer in that direction.</i>

982
00:58:21,623 --> 00:58:23,166
[reporter] <i>Are you getting the feeling</i>

983
00:58:23,249 --> 00:58:27,253
that some sort of movement is under way
that would ultimately erode Roe v. Wade?

984
00:58:27,921 --> 00:58:30,381
I'm not only getting a feeling.
I'm part of it.

985
00:58:31,132 --> 00:58:33,593
-[reporter 2] It's happened?
-It's happening.

986
00:58:33,885 --> 00:58:37,680
[Greenhouse] <i>The Americans United for Life</i>
<i>is one of the main players in this.</i>

987
00:58:39,057 --> 00:58:43,394
<i>They have a strategy of one anti-abortion</i>
<i>restriction at a time</i>

988
00:58:43,478 --> 00:58:47,315
<i>which could pass state legislatures</i>
<i>and maybe get up to the Supreme Court</i>

989
00:58:47,440 --> 00:58:49,025
<i>and overturn Roe against Wade.</i>

990
00:58:50,235 --> 00:58:52,320
<i>And it looked</i>
<i>like it actually might happen</i>

991
00:58:52,403 --> 00:58:54,822
<i>in an abortion case in 1989.</i>

992
00:58:55,281 --> 00:58:59,869
<i>But Justice O'Connor surprised the world</i>
<i>by sustaining Roe against Wade.</i>

993
00:59:00,495 --> 00:59:02,372
And that was a matter of

994
00:59:02,455 --> 00:59:05,959
extreme frustration
to the Court's conservatives.

995
00:59:06,960 --> 00:59:09,587
[woman] <i>I think Justice O'Connor</i>
<i>didn't want to be</i>

996
00:59:09,712 --> 00:59:11,589
the first and lone woman on the Court

997
00:59:11,714 --> 00:59:14,384
taking away
a settled constitutional right.

998
00:59:14,676 --> 00:59:16,844
And so she upheld Roe versus Wade.

999
00:59:18,137 --> 00:59:21,849
<i>But Justice Blackmun made</i>
<i>a very, very important statement,</i> <i>and he read it from the bench and he said,</i>
<i>"Roe versus Wade is hanging by a thread.</i>

1000
00:59:26,145 --> 00:59:28,523
We are in a very tenuous circumstance.

1001
00:59:28,606 --> 00:59:31,734
We're only one vote away.
The next case could do it."

1002
00:59:31,943 --> 00:59:35,780
And after that,
the political situation really changed.

1003
00:59:36,406 --> 00:59:40,451
Like a thousand points of light
in a broad and peaceful sky.

1004
