[Melich] <i>When H.W. became president,</i>

1005
00:59:43,830 --> 00:59:47,750
we thought that he would be
a pro-choice president.

1006
00:59:49,877 --> 00:59:53,298
Abortion divides. We have room
in our party for people that feel

1007
00:59:53,548 --> 00:59:56,509
one way, pro-life, or pro-choice.

1008
00:59:56,593 --> 00:59:58,595
This is an issue that divides.

1009
00:59:59,721 --> 01:00:01,222
[Melich] <i>When he was a congressman,</i>

1010
01:00:01,347 --> 01:00:06,102
<i>he had been known as a big supporter</i>
<i>of family planning, to the point that</i>

1011
01:00:06,561 --> 01:00:08,730
some of his colleagues
called him "Rubbers."

1012
01:00:09,230 --> 01:00:11,858
[reporter] Do you favor a constitutional
amendment against abortion?

1013
01:00:12,233 --> 01:00:13,860
I oppose such an amendment.

1014
01:00:14,110 --> 01:00:16,821
[announcer]
<i>The 35th Republican National Convention.</i>

1015
01:00:16,904 --> 01:00:18,698
What's the big challenge here this week?

1016
01:00:18,781 --> 01:00:21,534
I really don't know. I-- Abortion, mostly.

1017
01:00:22,327 --> 01:00:25,330
People really need to understand
that the pro-lifers

1018
01:00:25,413 --> 01:00:28,750
are now the backbone that is holding up
George Bush.

1019
01:00:28,958 --> 01:00:32,503
George Bush has to take
a strong pro-family position.

1020
01:00:32,670 --> 01:00:36,007
And frankly, that means
a strong position on abortion.

1021
01:00:39,010 --> 01:00:41,012
[Melich] And Bush turned against choice,

1022
01:00:41,304 --> 01:00:46,059
and he took on a position
that was stronger than...

1023
01:00:47,435 --> 01:00:49,020
than anything Reagan ever did.

1024
01:00:49,896 --> 01:00:52,065
I believe that abortion is wrong.

1025
01:00:52,649 --> 01:00:56,527
I believe that we should work
to overturn Roe vs. Wade.

1026
01:00:57,070 --> 01:01:00,698
<i>And I believe that states should have</i>
<i>the right to prohibit abortions.</i>

1027
01:01:01,616 --> 01:01:03,951
[man]<i> I don't make many guarantees,</i>
<i>but I'll make you one.</i>

1028
01:01:04,702 --> 01:01:06,663
Pennsylvania will be
the first state in the Union

1029
01:01:06,746 --> 01:01:09,499
to end the nightmare once and for all
and to outlaw abortion.

1030
01:01:09,624 --> 01:01:13,544
Supreme Court case number 91-744.

1031
01:01:13,670 --> 01:01:16,964
Planned Parenthood
of Southeast Pennsylvania versus Casey.

1032
01:01:17,423 --> 01:01:19,050
[Lee] <i>Planned Parenthood versus Casey.</i>

1033
01:01:19,217 --> 01:01:22,095
<i>That went up to the Supreme Court</i>
<i>in 1992.</i>

1034
01:01:22,178 --> 01:01:25,264
[Peter Jennings] ...one of the most
restrictive abortion laws in the nation.

1035
01:01:25,348 --> 01:01:28,142
And a lot of pro-life people thought
this was going to be the case

1036
01:01:28,226 --> 01:01:29,727
that would overturn Roe versus Wade.

1037
01:01:30,937 --> 01:01:33,481
[Jennings] <i>The Bush administration asked</i>
<i>the Supreme Court</i>

1038
01:01:33,815 --> 01:01:37,652
<i>to support further limitations</i>
<i>on a woman's right to have an abortion.</i>

1039
01:01:37,777 --> 01:01:40,363
[woman] <i>President Bush</i>
<i>has done all he can do</i>

1040
01:01:40,947 --> 01:01:44,617
to ensure that my arguments
are likely to fall on deaf ears.

1041
01:01:44,909 --> 01:01:48,413
[Kolbert]<i> I was totally convinced</i>
<i>that we were going to lose.</i>

1042
01:01:48,996 --> 01:01:50,373
For he has packed the Court

1043
01:01:50,832 --> 01:01:55,461
with justices who are hostile to a woman's
fundamental right to choose abortion.

1044
01:01:55,545 --> 01:01:58,214
Abortion litigation is a lot
like <i>Sesame Street.</i>

1045
01:01:58,381 --> 01:01:59,549
You got to learn to count.

1046
01:02:00,133 --> 01:02:02,260
<i>And the only number</i>
<i>that's important is five.</i>

1047
01:02:02,343 --> 01:02:04,178
<i>Are there five votes on the Supreme Court?</i>

1048
01:02:04,679 --> 01:02:06,472
Five votes that would overturn Roe.

1049
01:02:07,682 --> 01:02:10,101
He is the best person for this position.

1050
01:02:10,893 --> 01:02:13,980
<i>The president nominated Clarence Thomas</i>
<i>to the Supreme Court.</i>

1051
01:02:14,313 --> 01:02:17,775
<i>And I thought he would be the fifth vote</i>
<i>to overrule Roe.</i>

1052
01:02:21,320 --> 01:02:26,492
<i>And I remember there was a silence</i>
<i>in the courtroom that was palpable.</i>

1053
01:02:28,077 --> 01:02:29,162
[Chief Justice] <i>Ms. Kolbert.</i>

1054
01:02:29,245 --> 01:02:31,497
[Kolbert] <i>Mr. Chief Justice,</i>
<i>and may it please the Court.</i>

1055
01:02:32,206 --> 01:02:36,252
<i>Whether our Constitution endows</i>
<i>government with the power to force a woman</i>

1056
01:02:36,335 --> 01:02:39,255
<i>to continue or to end a pregnancy</i>
<i>against her will</i>

1057
01:02:39,672 --> 01:02:41,674
<i>is the central question in this case.</i>

1058
01:02:42,717 --> 01:02:46,637
And then the Solicitor General
of the United States stood up and argued

1059
01:02:46,971 --> 01:02:49,432
that Roe versus Wade
ought to be overturned.

1060
01:02:50,099 --> 01:02:53,394
[Solicitor General] <i>...the State does have</i>
<i>a compelling interest</i>

1061
01:02:53,686 --> 01:02:59,233
<i>in the potential life, in fetal life, and</i>
<i>that</i> <i>interest runs throughout pregnancy.</i>

1062
01:02:59,650 --> 01:03:02,945
But I wanted the Court
to understand the implications

1063
01:03:03,237 --> 01:03:07,575
of changing a standard
that was very protective for women.

1064
01:03:08,159 --> 01:03:11,204
[Kolbert] <i>This Court has recognized</i>
<i>that the rights of autonomy,</i>

1065
01:03:11,412 --> 01:03:16,459
<i>bodily integrity, and equality are central</i>
<i>to our notions of ordered liberty.</i>

1066
01:03:17,251 --> 01:03:19,629
<i>Roe lies at the heart of those interests.</i>

1067
01:03:20,922 --> 01:03:22,256
<i>Because, ultimately,</i>

1068
01:03:23,132 --> 01:03:24,759
abortion is not about whether or not

1069
01:03:24,842 --> 01:03:27,887
women should have
particular medical procedures.

1070
01:03:27,970 --> 01:03:29,055
It's about equality.

1071
01:03:29,138 --> 01:03:33,184
It's about a view of life,
about who should make important decisions.

1072
01:03:36,938 --> 01:03:39,148
<i>It's very rare that you know the date</i>

1073
01:03:39,357 --> 01:03:41,651
<i>that the Supreme Court is going</i>
<i>to issue a decision.</i>

1074
01:03:42,026 --> 01:03:45,488
You know that the case will be decided,
but you don't know when.

1075
01:03:47,031 --> 01:03:50,201
<i>But this time we knew when,</i>
<i>because every other case</i>

1076
01:03:50,868 --> 01:03:53,204
<i>that they heard that term</i>
<i>had already been decided.</i>

1077
01:03:54,163 --> 01:03:56,457
We're waiting outside
the Supreme Court now

1078
01:03:56,541 --> 01:03:58,751
for the announcement
of the Court's decision.

1079
01:04:00,211 --> 01:04:03,840
[Kolbert] <i>So, there were media trucks</i>
<i>parked outside.</i>

1080
01:04:04,382 --> 01:04:08,636
<i>Everybody was ready and waiting</i>
<i>for the overturning of Roe.</i>

1081
01:04:10,847 --> 01:04:13,099
[clerk] Release 91-45 Standing Orders.

1082
01:04:14,725 --> 01:04:18,229
[Kolbert] <i>The clerk of the court handed me</i>
<i>a copy of the decision.</i>

1083
01:04:18,479 --> 01:04:21,524
<i>And frankly I was confused</i>
<i>in many respects.</i>

1084
01:04:22,108 --> 01:04:24,652
<i>You know, it's a 50, 60 page opinion.</i>
<i>It's complicated.</i>

1085
01:04:24,735 --> 01:04:26,612
<i>You have to read it and understand it.</i>

1086
01:04:26,988 --> 01:04:30,366
At the same time,
I'm shepherded out to talk to

1087
01:04:30,867 --> 01:04:33,536
American media about what just happened.

1088
01:04:34,120 --> 01:04:37,582
I am Kathryn Kolbert.
I am counsel of record on behalf of

1089
01:04:37,957 --> 01:04:41,335
Planned Parenthood and the other
abortion clinics in Pennsylvania.

1090
01:04:41,419 --> 01:04:43,212
<i>It was a very ambiguous decision.</i>

1091
01:04:43,838 --> 01:04:46,716
Three Republican-appointed justices
had gotten together,

1092
01:04:48,134 --> 01:04:51,220
<i>and they decided that</i>
<i>rather than overturn Roe against Wade,</i>

1093
01:04:51,345 --> 01:04:52,930
<i>they were going to reformulate it...</i>

1094
01:04:53,890 --> 01:04:56,559
<i>with what they called</i>
<i>the undue burden standard.</i>

1095
01:04:58,436 --> 01:05:00,771
<i>So the Court upheld the right to abortion.</i>

1096
01:05:01,439 --> 01:05:05,318
<i>But the new standard meant</i>
<i>that states can undertake</i>

1097
01:05:05,401 --> 01:05:09,780
to persuade a woman to carry
a pregnancy to term,

1098
01:05:10,531 --> 01:05:14,201
but they cannot prevent a woman
from choosing abortion.

1099
01:05:14,952 --> 01:05:16,245
[Kolbert] <i>Under Roe versus Wade,</i>

1100
01:05:16,829 --> 01:05:19,457
<i>most abortion restrictions</i>
<i>were unconstitutional.</i>

1101
01:05:20,499 --> 01:05:22,960
<i>In Casey, the Court basically said that</i>

1102
01:05:23,044 --> 01:05:27,673
<i>states had the latitude to restrict</i>
<i>abortion in more ways than under Roe.</i>

1103
01:05:27,882 --> 01:05:31,719
Many, many kinds of restrictions,
waiting periods, informed consent.

1104
01:05:32,011 --> 01:05:36,766
Things found unconstitutional under Roe
have been validated by this Court.

1105
01:05:37,350 --> 01:05:41,020
And therefore we are much worse off
than we have been in the past.

1106
01:05:41,562 --> 01:05:44,565
<i>At the time, I thought, you know,</i>
<i>this is really horrible.</i>

1107
01:05:44,815 --> 01:05:46,734
...to place roadblocks
in the path of women...

1108
01:05:47,109 --> 01:05:50,947
<i>But whatever problems</i>
<i>the undue burden standard gave us,</i>

1109
01:05:51,656 --> 01:05:54,992
it was still preferable
than a total outlaw of abortion.

1110
01:05:55,076 --> 01:05:57,370
For a woman in need
of a medical procedure,

1111
01:05:57,828 --> 01:06:00,247
there's a big difference between having
to jump through hoops

1112
01:06:00,331 --> 01:06:02,249
<i>and not being able</i>
<i>to get the procedure at all.</i>

1113
01:06:03,709 --> 01:06:07,463
Four justices have said
Roe versus Wade must be overturned.

1114
01:06:08,214 --> 01:06:10,257
All it's going to take is one more

1115
01:06:10,549 --> 01:06:13,427
and I can only hope
that President Bush gets reelected.

1116
01:06:19,892 --> 01:06:22,603
[Clinton] It makes a difference
whether the president believes

1117
01:06:22,687 --> 01:06:25,439
in a woman's right to choose. And I do.

1118
01:06:25,523 --> 01:06:27,525
[applause]

1119
01:06:28,317 --> 01:06:29,986
[woman] <i>There was some momentum</i>

1120
01:06:30,069 --> 01:06:34,281
around the Clintons
and support for abortion rights.

1121
01:06:34,949 --> 01:06:38,077
[Clinton] <i>I am proud to nominate</i>
<i>Judge Ruth Bader Ginsburg to</i>

1122
01:06:38,160 --> 01:06:39,120
<i>the Supreme Court.</i>

1123
01:06:39,203 --> 01:06:43,582
It is essential to woman's equality
with man

1124
01:06:43,666 --> 01:06:45,918
<i>that she be the decision-maker.</i>

1125
01:06:46,711 --> 01:06:49,171
[Clinton] <i>I'm proud to nominate</i>
<i>Judge Stephen Breyer</i>

1126
01:06:49,338 --> 01:06:51,298
<i>to serve on the United States</i>
<i>Supreme Court.</i>

1127
01:06:51,590 --> 01:06:53,801
[Nash] <i>And there were bills pending</i>
<i>at the federal level</i>

1128
01:06:53,884 --> 01:06:56,512
<i>to protect access to abortion.</i>

1129
01:06:57,930 --> 01:07:01,017
The Clinton team has begun
to systematically wage war

1130
01:07:01,308 --> 01:07:02,685
against unborn children.

1131
01:07:03,352 --> 01:07:06,981
[Nash] <i>And abortion opponents were looking</i>
<i>for a way to stop this momentum.</i>

1132
01:07:07,857 --> 01:07:10,735
So they came up with this new idea and they honed in on later abortion.

1133
01:07:13,779 --> 01:07:16,866
Specifically they came up
with the term "partial birth abortion."

1134
01:07:21,328 --> 01:07:25,124
Some of you stay on this side,
some of you go on the other side, okay?

1135
01:07:25,207 --> 01:07:30,004
Not everyone. Try and spread out and get
the signs as many places as possible. [Newman] <i>Partial birth took off like</i>
<i>wildfire inside the pro-life movement.</i>

1136
01:07:35,342 --> 01:07:38,387
<i>It so horrified and shocked the conscience</i>

1137
01:07:38,929 --> 01:07:41,432
<i>and stripped this veil of respectability</i>

1138
01:07:41,515 --> 01:07:43,684
<i>from Planned Parenthood</i>
<i>and the abortionists.</i>

1139
01:07:43,768 --> 01:07:46,562
<i>It's terrible. Which side of the fence</i>
<i>are we gonna be on?</i>

1140
01:07:46,645 --> 01:07:48,272
We had to educate the public.

1141
01:07:48,355 --> 01:07:51,776
Are we gonna continue to support child
killing in America and call it choice?

1142
01:07:51,859 --> 01:07:56,030
We made it an issue.
We forced it on America.

1143
01:07:59,366 --> 01:08:01,077
This is partial birth abortion.

1144
01:08:01,577 --> 01:08:05,498
<i>The abortionist grabs the live baby's legs</i>
<i>with forceps.</i>

1145
01:08:06,082 --> 01:08:09,251
[Kolbert] <i>The Republicans introduced</i>
<i>the partial birth abortion law,</i>

1146
01:08:09,752 --> 01:08:11,378
<i>even though there's no such thing.</i>

1147
01:08:11,837 --> 01:08:14,965
<i>They made up the word</i>
<i>and it was a strategy</i>

1148
01:08:15,049 --> 01:08:17,134
<i>that really went to challenging</i>

1149
01:08:17,259 --> 01:08:20,054
the question of when late abortion
would be permitted.

1150
01:08:20,679 --> 01:08:24,058
With the idea that,
if you could push it earlier and earlier,

1151
01:08:24,225 --> 01:08:26,685
you could eliminate a number of abortions

1152
01:08:26,769 --> 01:08:30,773
And we knew immediately
that this was going to be a huge issue.

1153
01:08:30,856 --> 01:08:34,610
Abortion advocates are claiming that,
by banning partial-birth abortion,

1154
01:08:34,693 --> 01:08:37,446
we are mounting a direct attack
on Roe versus Wade.

1155
01:08:37,530 --> 01:08:41,408
For them, there is never an instance
when abortion is inappropriate.

1156
01:08:41,659 --> 01:08:44,203
For them,
the right to abortion is absolute

1157
01:08:44,286 --> 01:08:48,124
at whatever time, for whatever reason,
and in whatever way,

1158
01:08:48,249 --> 01:08:50,376
a woman or an abortionist chooses.

1159
01:08:51,377 --> 01:08:54,296
Ninety percent of women who have an
abortion have it in the first trimester.

1160
01:08:54,797 --> 01:08:56,841
<i>That's the vast majority of women.</i>

1161
01:08:57,216 --> 01:09:00,511
<i>And then a smaller proportion have it</i>
<i>before 20 weeks.</i>

1162
01:09:01,178 --> 01:09:04,265
<i>Between 20 and 24 weeks,</i>
<i>we're at probably about one percent.</i>

1163
01:09:04,348 --> 01:09:07,518
<i>And then, as we get further along, we're</i>
<i>getting to smaller and smaller numbers,</i>

1164
01:09:07,601 --> 01:09:09,103
<i>exceedingly low numbers.</i>

1165
01:09:09,436 --> 01:09:12,231
<i>So the majority of abortions</i>
<i>are in the first trimester.</i>

1166
01:09:12,565 --> 01:09:14,900
<i>But we spend most of our time</i>
<i>talking about</i>

1167
01:09:15,067 --> 01:09:17,361
<i>abortions that happened</i>
<i>in the second and third trimester.</i>

1168
01:09:17,653 --> 01:09:20,739
<i>And this is one of the strategies</i>
<i>of the anti-choice movement.</i>

1169
01:09:20,906 --> 01:09:23,033
Why do we call something
the partial-birth abortion,

1170
01:09:23,117 --> 01:09:25,161
when really that's not a medical term.

1171
01:09:25,244 --> 01:09:27,413
You always go after your enemy
where they're the weakest.

1172
01:09:27,496 --> 01:09:31,292
And they know that,
once we win, in the ninth month,

1173
01:09:31,458 --> 01:09:33,752
the rest of the card house
comes crumbling down.

1174
01:09:33,836 --> 01:09:35,129
We destroy their arguments.

1175
01:09:35,921 --> 01:09:37,965
They created a narrative that

1176
01:09:38,632 --> 01:09:40,509
women late in pregnancies were

1177
01:09:41,010 --> 01:09:44,722
killing their babies 'cause they,
you know, wanted to go to the gym instead.

1178
01:09:45,556 --> 01:09:47,933
Totally false. Doesn't happen.

1179
01:09:48,559 --> 01:09:52,813
<i>But there's no 30-second sound bite</i>
<i>to counter that image.</i>

1180
01:09:53,230 --> 01:09:56,108
<i>They were very good at creating optics,</i>

1181
01:09:56,275 --> 01:09:59,236
<i>creating language that supported</i>
<i>their point of view.</i>

1182
01:09:59,612 --> 01:10:03,324
<i>And so we had to figure out</i>
<i>how to challenge it politically.</i>

1183
01:10:03,616 --> 01:10:06,035
<i>And we were able</i>
<i>to introduce President Clinton</i>

1184
01:10:06,118 --> 01:10:09,955
<i>to women who would be affected</i>
<i>by the law.</i>

1185
01:10:10,331 --> 01:10:11,248
<i>Women who were</i>

1186
01:10:11,832 --> 01:10:15,085
losing pregnancies very late
or finding themselves

1187
01:10:15,377 --> 01:10:17,963
carrying a pregnancy
with very severe fetal anomalies.

1188
01:10:18,047 --> 01:10:21,550
Good morning. I'd like to thank
the subcommittee for inviting me here.

1189
01:10:22,259 --> 01:10:26,013
I went in for
a routine seven-month ultrasound.

1190
01:10:27,139 --> 01:10:30,184
They were saying,
"This looks good. This looks good."

1191
01:10:31,018 --> 01:10:33,354
Then suddenly, they got really quiet.

1192
01:10:34,355 --> 01:10:35,189
The doctor said,

1193
01:10:36,023 --> 01:10:38,984
"Your daughter has no eyes,
and her heart...

1194
01:10:40,444 --> 01:10:42,863
and other major organs are also failing.

1195
01:10:44,156 --> 01:10:46,492
And your child will not live."

1196
01:10:47,326 --> 01:10:48,369
[sniffles]

1197
01:10:50,454 --> 01:10:54,625
I remember just looking out the window.
I couldn't look at anybody.

1198
01:10:56,418 --> 01:11:01,674
So my mother-in-law asked, "Do we go on?
Does she have to go on?"

1199
01:11:04,218 --> 01:11:07,221
[Clinton] <i>This terrible problem affects</i>
<i>a few hundred Americans</i>

1200
01:11:07,930 --> 01:11:08,806
every year,

1201
01:11:09,723 --> 01:11:11,433
who desperately want their children,

1202
01:11:11,517 --> 01:11:14,436
are trying to building families and are
trying to strengthen their families.

1203
01:11:15,312 --> 01:11:16,939
And they should not become

1204
01:11:17,022 --> 01:11:19,566
<i>pawns in a larger debate.</i>

1205
01:11:19,817 --> 01:11:22,111
<i>And therefore I had no choice</i>
<i>but to veto the bill.</i>

1206
01:11:22,194 --> 01:11:25,739
I vetoed it just a few minutes ago
before I met with these families. [Nash] Bill Clinton vetoed it,
but it really spread.

1207
01:11:31,036 --> 01:11:34,873
And we started to see
new iterations of these bills,

1208
01:11:34,957 --> 01:11:38,627
using slightly different language,
in order to withstand a legal challenge.

1209
01:11:42,047 --> 01:11:45,592
It's a shame that child sacrifice
can be allowed in this country.

1210
01:11:45,676 --> 01:11:50,764
We are being arrested for speaking
and showing the truth of abortion.

1211
01:11:50,848 --> 01:11:52,308
Okay, careful. Walk carefully.

1212
01:11:52,391 --> 01:11:54,893
[Bush] <i>We need to ban</i>
<i>partial-birth abortions. I believe</i>

1213
01:11:54,977 --> 01:11:57,146
banning partial-birth abortions would be

1214
01:11:57,229 --> 01:12:01,734
a positive step toward reducing
the number of abortions in America.

1215
01:12:03,152 --> 01:12:06,613
We were able to get George W. Bush
elected with the promise that,

1216
01:12:06,697 --> 01:12:09,783
if we got another ban,
he'd pass it again and sign it.

1217
01:12:11,118 --> 01:12:13,787
<i>And he signed the federal ban into law,</i>

1218
01:12:14,538 --> 01:12:16,040
<i>and it went to the Supreme Court.</i>

1219
01:12:16,123 --> 01:12:19,752
[chanting] Hey, hey! Hi, ho!
Anti-choice has got to go!

1220
01:12:19,835 --> 01:12:22,796
[man]<i> The issue of abortion's</i>
<i>before the Supreme Court.</i>

1221
01:12:23,630 --> 01:12:27,343
Justice Sandra Day O'Connor announced
this morning that she will retire.

1222
01:12:28,135 --> 01:12:30,763
[reporter]
<i>Chief Justice William Rehnquist has died.</i>

1223
01:12:30,971 --> 01:12:32,389
[Bush] <i>The nomination power is one</i>

1224
01:12:32,473 --> 01:12:34,475
<i>of the most serious responsibilities</i>
<i>of a president.</i>

1225
01:12:35,184 --> 01:12:37,436
<i>I will nominate Judge Roberts</i>
<i>to the Supreme Court.</i>

1226
01:12:38,562 --> 01:12:41,065
And Chief Justice Roberts will have
as his colleague

1227
01:12:41,148 --> 01:12:43,108
<i>a proud member of</i>
<i>The Federalist Society,</i>

1228
01:12:43,734 --> 01:12:45,486
<i>Judge Sam Alito, Jr.</i>

1229
01:12:46,862 --> 01:12:50,074
<i>[reporter 1] In a 5-4 landmark decision,</i>
<i>the Court's new conservative majority</i>

1230
01:12:50,157 --> 01:12:52,493
<i>today upheld a nationwide ban</i>

1231
01:12:52,868 --> 01:12:55,162
<i>on a procedure critics call</i>
<i>partial-birth abortion.</i>

1232
01:12:55,662 --> 01:12:58,624
[reporter 2] <i>In court, an angry</i>
<i>Justice Ruth Bader Ginsburg</i>

1233
01:12:58,707 --> 01:13:01,752
<i>took the unusual step of</i>
<i>reading her dissent aloud.</i>

1234
01:13:03,629 --> 01:13:08,300
[Justice Ginsburg]
<i>I strongly dissent from today's opinion.</i>

1235
01:13:09,093 --> 01:13:13,097
<i>The Partial-Birth Abortion Ban Act</i>
<i>cannot be understood</i>

1236
01:13:13,180 --> 01:13:15,682
<i>as anything other than an effort</i>

1237
01:13:16,058 --> 01:13:17,893
<i>to chip away at a right</i>

1238
01:13:18,310 --> 01:13:20,604
<i>declared in Roe v. Wade.</i>

1239
01:13:24,441 --> 01:13:25,776
[Perry] <i>Roe versus Wade</i>

1240
01:13:26,944 --> 01:13:29,196
<i>prevents us from prohibiting abortion.</i>

1241
01:13:29,363 --> 01:13:30,864
<i>But it does allow us,</i>

1242
01:13:31,865 --> 01:13:33,826
<i>the states, to...</i>

1243
01:13:34,326 --> 01:13:36,453
do some things to protect life,

1244
01:13:36,954 --> 01:13:41,375
if they can show there is
a compelling state interest.

1245
01:13:41,917 --> 01:13:45,421
Governor Rick Perry wanted to end
access to reproductive health care.

1246
01:13:45,838 --> 01:13:48,757
And because the legislature is
so disproportionately

1247
01:13:49,091 --> 01:13:51,301
uh, led by the Republican party,

1248
01:13:51,718 --> 01:13:55,931
<i>they proposed abortion restrictions, which</i>
<i>were the most extreme in the country.</i>

1249
01:13:57,349 --> 01:14:02,146
House Bill 2 was a good example of these
kinds of laws that were being passed in

1250
01:14:02,646 --> 01:14:04,648
<i>many states controlled by the Republicans.</i>

1251
01:14:05,065 --> 01:14:08,527
<i>Laws that really focused</i>
<i>on where the abortion could be performed</i>

1252
01:14:08,819 --> 01:14:13,073
<i>and regulations to either the doctor's</i>
<i>office or a surgical center.</i>

1253
01:14:13,157 --> 01:14:15,534
Thank you for calling
the Southwestern Women's Surgery Center.

1254
01:14:15,617 --> 01:14:17,327
This is Alicia. How may I help you?

1255
01:14:17,411 --> 01:14:19,997
This is what are known as TRAP laws: Targeted Regulation of Abortion Providers.

1256
01:14:23,834 --> 01:14:27,629
And the purpose of these laws is
to make it as difficult as possible

1257
01:14:27,838 --> 01:14:29,214
<i>to provide abortion services,</i>

1258
01:14:29,631 --> 01:14:31,758
prohibit as many abortions as you can,

1259
01:14:31,925 --> 01:14:34,219
make the ones that do occur
as expensive as possible.

1260
01:14:34,303 --> 01:14:35,846
<i>It's so obvious what they're doing.</i>

1261
01:14:37,723 --> 01:14:40,434
My goal is to make abortion,

1262
01:14:40,642 --> 01:14:43,562
at any stage, a thing of the past.

1263
01:14:43,937 --> 01:14:45,939
[applause]

1264
01:14:46,773 --> 01:14:50,152
So these restrictions would shut down
dozens of women's health centers

1265
01:14:50,235 --> 01:14:51,487
<i>all across Texas.</i>

1266
01:14:52,112 --> 01:14:54,323
<i>And that's why Senator Wendy Davis</i>

1267
01:14:54,406 --> 01:14:57,034
<i>decided to stand up and fight</i>
<i>for the rights of women.</i>

1268
01:15:00,037 --> 01:15:01,955
[Davis] <i>So this bill went to the Senate.</i>

1269
01:15:02,831 --> 01:15:07,336
<i>But, because it was the final day</i>
<i>of the session, the clock was ticking.</i>

1270
01:15:07,878 --> 01:15:11,507
<i>And that gave me an opportunity</i>
<i>for the filibuster.</i>

1271
01:15:11,882 --> 01:15:14,176
Members, I'm rising on the floor today...

1272
01:15:14,384 --> 01:15:19,973
That meant I had about 13 hours of talking
to make sure that this bill did not pass.

1273
01:15:21,642 --> 01:15:24,811
<i>The rules in Texas say</i>
<i>that you cannot have a sip of water,</i>

1274
01:15:24,895 --> 01:15:26,313
<i>you cannot have anything to drink,</i>

1275
01:15:26,396 --> 01:15:30,108
<i>you cannot lean on your desk</i>
<i>and you certainly cannot leave the floor</i>

1276
01:15:30,400 --> 01:15:31,527
<i>to go to the restroom.</i>

1277
01:15:32,486 --> 01:15:37,950
So I had a pair of running shoes
on my feet and I had a catheter bag.

1278
01:15:38,033 --> 01:15:41,203
A doctor had come over
at about six o'clock that morning

1279
01:15:41,328 --> 01:15:44,998
and inserted a catheter so that
I'd be able to make it through the day.

1280
01:15:46,208 --> 01:15:48,460
Senator Wendy Davis must make it
to midnight.

1281
01:15:48,544 --> 01:15:50,462
That is the end of the special session.

1282
01:15:50,671 --> 01:15:53,590
Essentially she's wasting time,
running out the clock.

1283
01:15:53,674 --> 01:15:57,219
The way she's doing that? Right now,
she's reading letters from Texas women

1284
01:15:57,511 --> 01:15:59,388
<i>who oppose this legislation.</i>

1285
01:15:59,930 --> 01:16:02,558
...in order for their voices to be heard.

1286
01:16:02,641 --> 01:16:06,270
-...told me any pregnancy will be very...
-[Kolbert] <i>And the filibuster went viral.</i>

1287
01:16:06,853 --> 01:16:08,522
Not only was she a woman

1288
01:16:08,647 --> 01:16:12,234
opposing the bill, but she was one
of the only women in the room.

1289
01:16:12,693 --> 01:16:15,112
<i>It was an internet moment.</i> [Richards] <i>People had left their kids</i>
<i>with their neighbors</i>

1290
01:16:23,829 --> 01:16:25,789
<i>and driven hours to Austin to be there.</i>

1291
01:16:26,331 --> 01:16:28,542
<i>Students had left their college campuses</i>

1292
01:16:28,625 --> 01:16:31,253
<i>and came to Austin</i>
<i>to hear Wendy filibuster.</i>

1293
01:16:31,962 --> 01:16:34,339
These are Texans who relied
on the minority...

1294
01:16:34,423 --> 01:16:35,799
[Richards] <i>I'm a Texan.</i>

1295
01:16:35,882 --> 01:16:39,094
<i>Never seen the outpouring of activism</i>
<i>like we saw there.</i>

1296
01:16:39,469 --> 01:16:41,722
You literally could not get
in the capitol.

1297
01:16:41,888 --> 01:16:44,558
Every annex was full, every room was full.

1298
01:16:45,475 --> 01:16:46,518
<i>It was extraordinary.</i>

1299
01:16:46,810 --> 01:16:49,646
...another ruling she made
was if there was a...

1300
01:16:49,855 --> 01:16:52,649
[Davis] <i>And about 15 minutes</i>
<i>before midnight,</i>

1301
01:16:53,150 --> 01:16:55,694
<i>procedural rules of order were broken...</i>

1302
01:16:56,403 --> 01:16:57,487
[man] <i>...and the third...</i>

1303
01:16:57,613 --> 01:17:00,282
[Davis] <i>...in order to bring</i>
<i>my filibuster to an end.</i>

1304
01:17:01,283 --> 01:17:03,744
<i>And the people who were there</i>
<i>understood</i>

1305
01:17:03,827 --> 01:17:08,332
<i>that rules were being broken</i>
<i>in order to silence opposition to a bill.</i>

1306
01:17:08,415 --> 01:17:11,293
[man] After consultation
with the parliamentarian and after...

1307
01:17:11,460 --> 01:17:14,588
-[Davis] <i>And they'd had enough.</i>
-...well taken and is sustained.

1308
01:17:15,005 --> 01:17:15,881
[woman] Bullshit!

1309
01:17:15,964 --> 01:17:18,175
The chair recognizes Senator...

1310
01:17:18,258 --> 01:17:19,468
[crowd yelling]

1311
01:17:19,551 --> 01:17:22,429
[chanting] Let her speak!
Let her speak! Let her speak!

1312
01:17:22,512 --> 01:17:25,057
Let her speak! Let her speak!
Let her speak!

1313
01:17:29,311 --> 01:17:31,897
Wendy! Wendy! Wendy! Wendy!

1314
01:17:31,980 --> 01:17:34,858
Wendy! Wendy!
Wendy! Wendy!

1315
01:17:34,941 --> 01:17:37,444
Wendy! Wendy! Wendy! Wendy!

1316
01:17:39,321 --> 01:17:41,239
[Davis] <i>And as they began to scream,</i>

1317
01:17:42,199 --> 01:17:45,202
<i>everyone up and down the hallways</i>
<i>began to scream,</i>

1318
01:17:45,285 --> 01:17:49,164
<i>and at every level of the rotunda</i>
<i>and outside on the capitol lawn.</i>

1319
01:17:50,916 --> 01:17:52,918
<i>And I could literally feel</i>

1320
01:17:53,001 --> 01:17:56,296
<i>the vibration of their voices</i>
<i>and their energy</i>

1321
01:17:56,380 --> 01:17:57,923
<i>and the pounding of their feet.</i>

1322
01:17:58,507 --> 01:18:01,551
[man] If I can have order.
We are in the middle of a vote.

1323
01:18:03,011 --> 01:18:04,429
The secretary has started the vote.

1324
01:18:05,013 --> 01:18:07,057
[Davis] <i>It ate up enough of the clock</i>

1325
01:18:07,140 --> 01:18:10,936
<i>that the final vote wasn't taken</i>
<i>until 12:03.</i>

1326
01:18:11,269 --> 01:18:14,856
Members, it's now past midnight. And so...

1327
01:18:14,940 --> 01:18:18,193
And it became known
as the people's filibuster. Rightly so.

1328
01:18:19,194 --> 01:18:21,530
[Richards] This is straight from
Senator Wendy Davis, okay?

1329
01:18:21,905 --> 01:18:22,739
Hold your applause.

1330
01:18:23,782 --> 01:18:26,201
First, "I love you guys." Okay? -[crowd whooping]
-We love you, too, Wendy!

1331
01:18:29,079 --> 01:18:32,624
[crowd cheers]

1332
01:18:34,501 --> 01:18:39,464
"So the lieutenant governor has agreed
that SB-5 is dead."

1333
01:18:39,548 --> 01:18:41,550
[cheering]

1334
01:18:55,230 --> 01:18:58,191
[Perry] <i>The woman who filibustered</i>
<i>the Senate the other day,</i>

1335
01:18:59,943 --> 01:19:02,571
<i>she was born into difficult circumstances.</i>

1336
01:19:02,988 --> 01:19:04,740
<i>She's the daughter of a single woman.</i>

1337
01:19:05,449 --> 01:19:07,367
<i>She was a teenage mother herself.</i>

1338
01:19:08,034 --> 01:19:12,247
<i>She managed to eventually graduate</i>
<i>from Harvard Law School</i>

1339
01:19:12,622 --> 01:19:14,708
<i>and serve in the Texas Senate.</i>

1340
01:19:15,917 --> 01:19:16,918
<i>It's unfortunate</i>

1341
01:19:17,669 --> 01:19:20,005
that she hasn't learned
from her own example

1342
01:19:20,589 --> 01:19:24,593
that every life must be given a chance
to realize its full potential

1343
01:19:24,676 --> 01:19:26,511
and that every life matters.

1344
01:19:26,595 --> 01:19:28,054
[applause]

1345
01:19:28,138 --> 01:19:30,056
[Davis] <i>We had successfully</i>
<i>killed the bill.</i>

1346
01:19:30,140 --> 01:19:32,768
But we were called right back
within a few days.

1347
01:19:33,101 --> 01:19:37,230
And, of course, this time
there was no way to filibuster.

1348
01:19:37,397 --> 01:19:41,318
<i>♪ Where have all the babies gone? ♪</i>

1349
01:19:41,568 --> 01:19:46,072
<i>♪ I pray to heaven for every one ♪</i>

1350
01:19:46,156 --> 01:19:47,824
[reporter] <i>Get ready to do it all again.</i>

1351
01:19:47,908 --> 01:19:50,911
<i>Governor Rick Perry called</i>
<i>a special session early this evening.</i>

1352
01:19:54,247 --> 01:19:56,166
[man] We talked about the choice.

1353
01:19:56,333 --> 01:19:59,336
Do you think if the mother had
a conversation with the baby and said,

1354
01:19:59,544 --> 01:20:03,006
"You know, this just isn't really
convenient to give birth to you right now.

1355
01:20:03,173 --> 01:20:04,466
Do you mind dying?"

1356
01:20:04,633 --> 01:20:06,051
[woman] I can't take it anymore!

1357
01:20:07,052 --> 01:20:09,638
-I think--
-That was very offensive!

1358
01:20:09,930 --> 01:20:11,932
[man] I think that baby would say--

1359
01:20:12,682 --> 01:20:14,518
This is an assault on women!

1360
01:20:16,478 --> 01:20:18,522
I don't get mad with those folks.
I pray for her.

1361
01:20:18,605 --> 01:20:19,815
[woman] You are failing Texas!

1362
01:20:20,565 --> 01:20:22,859
You are failing Texas!

1363
01:20:31,493 --> 01:20:33,036
[Davis] In just a few moments,

1364
01:20:33,578 --> 01:20:35,455
we are going to vote on a bill

1365
01:20:35,539 --> 01:20:39,751
that has deeply and profoundly divided us.

1366
01:20:40,794 --> 01:20:42,796
<i>Separating us by political party...</i>

1367
01:20:44,548 --> 01:20:45,674
<i>by gender...</i>

1368
01:20:46,299 --> 01:20:47,926
<i>by life experience...</i>

1369
01:20:48,510 --> 01:20:51,263
<i>by what our religious beliefs bind us to.</i>

1370
01:20:51,346 --> 01:20:53,431
[chanting] Not in this life!

1371
01:20:53,598 --> 01:20:58,895
<i>We all believe in the beauty</i>
<i>and the wonder that is human life.</i>

1372
01:21:00,355 --> 01:21:03,358
<i>But I also believe that women already here</i>

1373
01:21:04,359 --> 01:21:05,360
<i>are beautiful.</i>

1374
01:21:06,403 --> 01:21:08,154
<i>And that they deserve to live,</i>

1375
01:21:09,114 --> 01:21:12,826
<i>they deserve to determine</i>
<i>the direction of their lives,</i>

1376
01:21:13,618 --> 01:21:17,873
<i>they deserve to be recognized</i>
<i>as full people...</i>

1377
01:21:19,916 --> 01:21:23,086
<i>fully capable</i>
<i>of making difficult decisions</i>

1378
01:21:23,336 --> 01:21:27,632
<i>with the help of their family,</i>
<i>their doctor and their God.</i>

1379
01:21:28,133 --> 01:21:31,136
[chanting] Wendy! Wendy! Wendy! Wendy!

1380
01:21:31,219 --> 01:21:34,764
Wendy! Wendy!
Wendy! Wendy!

1381
01:21:36,433 --> 01:21:39,227
No woman should be judged by someone else,

1382
01:21:39,895 --> 01:21:43,607
someone who believes
they would have made a different decision.

1383
01:21:44,941 --> 01:21:47,777
No woman should be judged by someone else,

1384
01:21:48,528 --> 01:21:52,699
because these decisions
are never ever easy.

1385
01:21:53,742 --> 01:21:56,411
They're not made casually or quickly.

1386
01:21:56,745 --> 01:22:01,750
And those of us in the Senate
should refuse to make this decision

1387
01:22:02,292 --> 01:22:04,377
casually or quickly.

1388
01:22:04,878 --> 01:22:07,547
Because the fight for the future of Texas

1389
01:22:08,214 --> 01:22:09,382
is just beginning.

1390
01:22:10,425 --> 01:22:12,135
Thank you, Mr. President.
Thank you, members.

1391
01:22:14,220 --> 01:22:18,600
There being 19 ayes and 11 nays,
House Bill 2 is finally passed.

1392
01:22:18,683 --> 01:22:22,812
[chanting]
We won't go back! We won't go back!

1393
01:22:23,271 --> 01:22:26,483
We won't go back!
We won't go back!

1394
01:22:26,566 --> 01:22:27,400
Come on!

1395
01:22:27,776 --> 01:22:29,152
We won't go back! We won't go back!

1396
01:22:33,448 --> 01:22:37,369
It is our responsibility to improve
the quality of care for women

1397
01:22:37,452 --> 01:22:38,328
in the state.

1398
01:22:39,454 --> 01:22:42,082
[Davis] <i>Of course, the argument was made</i>
<i>all along that somehow</i>

1399
01:22:42,332 --> 01:22:44,834
this is being done in the interests
of women's health.

1400
01:22:45,210 --> 01:22:50,548
And in spite of incredible scientific
pushback to that statement,

1401
01:22:50,674 --> 01:22:52,300
House Bill 2 passed.

1402
01:22:52,842 --> 01:22:55,136
Shame! Shame! Shame!

1403
01:22:55,595 --> 01:22:56,888
Shame! Shame! Shame!

1404
01:23:01,017 --> 01:23:06,022
<i>The law went into effect and over half of</i>
<i>our abortion clinics in the state closed.</i>

1405
01:23:09,734 --> 01:23:12,529
<i>We went from 41 clinics to 19</i>

1406
01:23:12,612 --> 01:23:15,031
<i>as a consequence</i>
<i>of the implementation of the law.</i>

1407
01:23:16,700 --> 01:23:18,243
<i>In central Texas,</i>

1408
01:23:18,535 --> 01:23:20,286
<i>there were no clinics left open.</i>

1409
01:23:21,830 --> 01:23:23,873
<i>And that was pretty demoralizing.</i>

1410
01:23:24,833 --> 01:23:28,169
<i>But there was something really important</i>
<i>that had happened.</i>

1411
01:23:28,920 --> 01:23:34,467
We as a state woke up to the reality
of an assault on women.

1412
01:23:35,218 --> 01:23:38,054
We woke up to the reality of our power.

1413
01:23:38,930 --> 01:23:42,267
And it's a power that has continued
to grow.

1414
01:23:47,022 --> 01:23:50,233
[reporter] <i>The first major abortion case</i>
<i>in almost a decade.</i>

1415
01:23:50,316 --> 01:23:54,320
<i>It centers on a case in Texas</i>
<i>that has already forced clinics to close</i>

1416
01:23:54,404 --> 01:23:56,656
<i>and could force even more</i>
<i>to close down as well.</i>

1417
01:23:57,741 --> 01:24:01,995
The stakes are huge. And they're not just
huge for Texas women.

1418
01:24:02,495 --> 01:24:04,539
They're huge for women
all over the country.

1419
01:24:04,998 --> 01:24:06,541
Anti-choice! Anti-women!

